# Small-Team Workflow — local SQLite + BYO Postgres sync hub

> **Project:** {{ .ProjectPrefix }}
> **Generated by:** mtix {{ .Version }}
> **Workflow audience:** 2-10 trusted developers sharing one Postgres
> sync hub (Supabase, Neon, RDS, or self-hosted). Suitable for small
> startups and OSS team adoption.

> **Trust banner.** The sync hub is a replication mechanism, not a
> tenancy boundary. Anyone with the hub DSN can read every event ever
> pushed. Treat the DSN like a production database credential.

In this workflow every developer's CLI keeps its **own local SQLite**
as the canonical store (`.mtix/data/mtix.db`). Mutations emit events
to a local queue; `mtix sync push` ships the queue to the BYO Postgres
hub; `mtix sync pull` replays others' events into the local store.
`.mtix/tasks.json` remains the human-readable git-tracked snapshot.

---

## Setup steps

### 1. Provision a Postgres hub

Managed (Supabase, Neon, RDS) or self-hosted. Make sure TLS with a
trusted CA is enabled. Note the host, port, database name.

### 2. Create a least-privilege role for mtix

Run as a PG superuser once during provisioning. The role only needs
INSERT/SELECT on the 5 mtix-owned tables:

```sql
CREATE ROLE mtix_sync LOGIN PASSWORD 'set-a-strong-one';
CREATE DATABASE mtix_hub OWNER mtix_sync;
\c mtix_hub
GRANT CONNECT ON DATABASE mtix_hub TO mtix_sync;
GRANT USAGE, CREATE ON SCHEMA public TO mtix_sync;
-- mtix_sync needs CREATE during initial migration only; revoke after.
```

After `mtix sync init` has run once, drop schema-level CREATE:

```sql
REVOKE CREATE ON SCHEMA public FROM mtix_sync;
```

### 3. Store the DSN

Two sources, in order of preference:

```bash
# Preferred (production): env var
export MTIX_SYNC_DSN="postgresql://mtix_sync@hub.example.com:5432/mtix_hub?sslmode=verify-full"

# Alternative (dev convenience): per-project secrets file
echo 'postgresql://mtix_sync@hub.example.com:5432/mtix_hub?sslmode=verify-full' > .mtix/secrets
chmod 0600 .mtix/secrets
# .mtix/secrets is auto-gitignored by 'mtix sync init'
```

**Never commit the DSN to a tracked yaml.** `mtix sync init` scans
`.mtix/config.{yaml,yml,json}` for DSN-shaped keys and **refuses to
proceed** if any are present (fail-closed).

### 4. Initialize the hub (one teammate, once)

From one team machine:

```bash
mtix sync init
```

This runs schema migration (single-flighted via PG advisory lock),
registers your project on the hub (`sync_projects` table with the
project's first_event_hash), and pushes the local history. Subsequent
teammates clone instead — see step 5.

### 5. Clone from the hub (every other teammate)

From each other team machine, in a fresh checkout:

```bash
mtix sync clone
```

Pulls the full event log from the hub and replays it into the local
SQLite. Idempotent — re-running clone after the initial pull is a
no-op (per `applied_events` dedupe).

### 6. Daily flow

```bash
# Pull teammate work before you start
mtix sync pull

# Make changes via the normal CLI
mtix create "..." && mtix update ... && mtix done ...

# Push your queue to the hub
mtix sync push

# Check status when in doubt about pending items
mtix sync status
```

### 7. Install the pre-push hook (recommended)

```bash
cp examples/hooks/pre-push .git/hooks/pre-push
chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-push
```

The hook calls `mtix sync push` before `git push`. It honors
`MTIX_SYNC_HOOK=1` (set automatically by the hook script): transient
hub-unreachable errors warn-and-skip rather than blocking the push.

### 8. (Optional) Run the daemon for periodic auto-push

For durability across machine loss, install the daemon as a
systemd / launchd service:

```bash
# Print the systemd unit file (Linux) — operator places it
mtix sync daemon --install | sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/mtix-sync.service
sudo systemctl enable --now mtix-sync
```

The daemon runs `mtix sync pull` on an interval (default 30s) and
keeps the local view fresh. See the [safety-critical
workflow](safety-critical.md) for full guidance on hardening the
service.

