## Conflict handling

When two teammates edit the same field concurrently, the hub
records the contention in `sync_conflicts` and the apply layer
resolves it via Last-Write-Wins (deterministic by lamport →
wall_clock_ts → author_machine_hash).

```bash
# Inspect the contested entries
mtix sync conflicts list

# Resolve a specific conflict (per-conflict, surgical)
mtix sync conflicts resolve <id> --keep-local
mtix sync conflicts resolve <id> --keep-remote

# Whole-project escape hatch (only if many conflicts at once)
mtix sync reconcile --dry-run
mtix sync reconcile --discard-local   # accept hub state
mtix sync reconcile --rename-to NEWPREFIX  # publish locally under a fresh prefix
mtix sync reconcile --import-as PARENT-ID  # graft local nodes under a hub node
```

LWW is deterministic — every CLI ends up at the same final state
regardless of the order in which they pull. Conflicts are recorded
for auditability, not because the system is uncertain.

**Note:** When two CLIs share `authorID="cli"` (the default), their
concurrent events produce vector clocks that are `Equal()` rather
than `Concurrent()`, so the hub does NOT log a `sync_conflicts` row
even though LWW still resolves the contention. If audit-trail
completeness for same-authorID conflicts matters, set distinct
authorIDs per agent. See `docs/SECURITY-MODEL.md` for the full
tradeoff discussion.

