## Trust boundary

**What this workflow protects against:**

- Network adversaries between each CLI and the hub, via mandatory
  `sslmode=verify-full`.
- DSN leakage in logs, errors, MCP output, and panic traces — every
  error string flows through `redact.DSN`; `defer redact.Recover`
  wraps `main()` so panics with a DSN in scope are redacted before
  the runtime prints them.
- SQL injection in event payloads — parameterized queries throughout;
  audited in MTIX-9.1 (SQLite) and MTIX-15.3 / MTIX-15.11 audit pass
  2 (transport).
- Silent data loss — the local queue is durable until pushed;
  queue-full surfaces `ErrSyncQueueFull` rather than dropping.
- Audit-log tampering — PG triggers raise on UPDATE/DELETE of
  `audit_log` and `sync_conflicts`.
- Replay of pushed events — `applied_events.event_id` dedupes.

**What this workflow does NOT protect against:**

- A teammate intentionally tampering with task data — anyone with the
  DSN has full read/write.
- A teammate bypassing the pre-push hook with `git push --no-verify` —
  hooks are advisory.
- A compromised PG provider — hub data is as private as the hosting
  PG instance.
- A PG superuser disabling triggers — see [safety-critical
  workflow](safety-critical.md) for hardening.
- Lost un-pushed events — explicit operational practice (daemon +
  push-before-step-away) is the mitigation.
- Multi-tenant isolation — the hub is one shared database.

